This is a basic cr-10S4 printer model for use in Simplify3d (To show the printer frame within the viewing window). It is NOT intended to be 100% accurate, nor is it intended to be printed or used for creating accessories/parts for the cr-10 printer.

Jantzen Day's Instructions on how to incorporate such a model into your Simplify3d profiles can be found here:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jkudSgv_uTY
He also provides a link to a standard cr-10 model in that video.

I mixed this model from his standard cr-10 (300x300) .stl provided within that video, and then added the control box to remind users which is the front of the machine (in case they lose sight of the origin marks often like I do). Of note, I removed the end caps, except those that were modeled into the extrusion. Sorry, realized too late they were not all separate endcaps, and weren't really needed for this application.

Thanks to Jantzen Day, and Edwin Van Het Bolscher of the Creality CR-10 3d Printer User Group who provided Jantzen with the original CR-10 model that both he & I then edited for use in Simplify3D.

author: revolvermann76

description.text:
• 2x5ml glass syringes
  • 20xM6 nuts
  • 2xM3 bolts
  • one 3 mm rod axis
  • 4 pieces of 2mm rod
  • 4x2mm ball bearings
  • 2x3mm ball bearings
  • several PLA meters !!!
  • 2 pieces of wood
  • one candel
  • 10 cm of 3mm ID silicon tubing
    • and you get a (not yet) beautiful, fully functionnal 3D printed Stirling engine.
    Just see it on youtube: http://youtu.be/NecriSICN7w edit : please see the #2 motor here : http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:278422

All part are printed in PLA using Slic3R with an infill density of 0.5.
All holes shall be drilled to exact diameter:
  • main axis = 3mm
  • seringe heads and whell pin = 2 mm
  • main axis ball bearing = 6.5 mm
  • head rod ball bearing = 5 mm
    • Before printing the inertia wheels, I would advice to first print 2 test pieces (M3 and M6.stl) to check that the nuts fits correctly into the holes...
    Adapt the size in .scad files... The M6 nuts are needed to give some inertia to the wheels. They fit smoothly into the hexagonal holes. If you get some play, just use a soldering iron to melt the PLA lip and seal the nut in right position. The syringes head also fits smoothly into the plastic head and can be easily unmounted. see http://youtu.be/fF49rg12fj8
    The syringes pistons shall be run in using car repair very thin sand paper. Support of the two seringues cannot (a shame) be printed as the syringe body may become quite hot ...
    I've to find a way to print something using some thermal insulation...
    By now, I must admit my wooden support is uggly, I just wanted to make a first demonstration of the proof of concept !

I've configured the latest Marlin Firmware 1.1.6 for the CTC i3 and I'd like to share it with you guys so you don't have to worry about that. There are 2 Firmwares inside the Zip: Stock Configuration and Auto Bed Leveling. You should use the Stock Configuration if you've made no adjustments to your printer hardware. If you've got an inductive sensor, just use the Auto Bed Leveling firmware and everything's setup for you. I've also attached my Sensor Mount which you can use. The Firmware is already adjusted to the Mounting Plate so you shouldn't have to change anything.

Features of the new Firmware:

  • Latest Marlin firmware 1.1.6 with lots of improvements
  • (Auto Bed Leveling) depending on your choice
  • Linear Advance feature - better print quality
  • Advanced Pause feature - change Filament easily mid print
  • EEPROM - store the Settings you've made
  • Printer Statistics - see how much Prints you've done and how much Filament you've used
  • Emergency Commands - cancle prints while the Buffer is still full
  • Control both heaters simultaneously
  • Calibrated Steps/mm (were wrong on default Firmware)
  • Adjusted Preheat constants for what worked the best for me with this printer
  • Added an LCD Info Menu where you can get all the informations about your printer quickly

This Firmware is made for the ATmega2560 but also works with ATmega1280 chip. You will most likely have to flash a bootloader using an USBASP / Arduino UNO if you haven't done that already. Just do a quick google search and you will find lots of information about that.

Have fun with your fresh Marlin Firmware.

title: Sony Action Cam Hinged Wall Mount Holder (AS200V)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
What is this thing?

This is a lightweight hinged wall mount holder for the Sony HDR-AS200V action cam.

Here is a two-part "making of" video:

  • part_1 modelling in SketchUp, 3d printing
  • part_2 post-print processing, assembly, and installation

Depending on your printer's tolerances the cam should slide in quite easily into the holder. To be on the safe side I added a 4mm screw hole at the bottom-front that matches the according thread on the bottom of the cam.

There's a cavity on the front left-hand side so that the prev/next buttons can be reached. They are the only way to turn on the cam without immediately going into recording mode (which is the behaviour of the record button on the backside).

The slot in the bottom allows access to the "Multi" hatch. I use it to power the cam when the recording time is likely to exceed the battery power.

The holder and the wall mount are connected with a 6mm threaded rod.

The wall mount has only one screw hole. On purpose, I may add, so you can easily adjust the slope. I use a washer to spread the screw's pressure on a bigger area.

Payload

  • The 3D printed parts.
  • 1 x 4mm diameter threaded bar approx. 18mm
  • 1 x 6mm diameter threaded bar approx. 58mm
  • 1 x M4 flat nut
  • 1 x M6 nut
  • Super glue or two-component adhesive

Assembly

  1. Glue the small knob to a 4mm diameter threaded bar of approximately 18mm length. I used two-component adhesive. You should take care that the threaded bar is sticking out no more than 7mm from the knob.
  2. Insert the M6 nut into its designated place on the wall mount. If the slot is too small, don't force it! Use a heat gun to gently(!) heat the slot, then insert the nut.
  3. Glue the big knob to a 6mm diameter threaded bar of approximately 58mm length. Again, I used two-component adhesive. Take care that the threaded bar does not go too far into the knob. I suggest to put the holder in its place in the wall mount, screw in the bar so it shows through the nut and then, on the opposite side, mark the position on the threaded bar till where you will insert the threaded bar into the big knob. Now disassemble everything and glue the knob to the bar.
  4. Glue the flat M4 nut in its designated slot in the holder. If the slot is too small, gently heat the slot, then insert the nut. A drop of super glue might help.
  5. Screw the small knob into the bottom hole of the holder.
  6. Screw the wall mount to the wall using the screw hole.
  7. Insert the holder, insert the 6mm diameter threaded bar with the big knob.
  8. Insert the camera and bolt it down with the small knob. Do not use too much force!
  9. Enjoy! :-)

description.text:
This is a remix of a clever clip-on design, that I have tailored to my requirements. The item that I based my design on had space to mount LED-strips, but I didn't need it, and my camera is an old Creative webcam which needed a different mounting solution.

I have only provided files for the two parts that I modified; please see the link to item I remixed for the neatly-designed clip-on mounting bracket for the z-axis.

Note: in the image, the clip-on bracket (original designer's part) joins the slide-mount with a hinge. I have used a paperclip as the hinge-pin, which works rather well.

The 4.5mm hole in the sliding camera-mount is for a screw; my intention was to tap it to 5mm and use a screw to hold the slider in place, but it is not required in practice.

When printing, I used supports on the camera-mount part. Both STLs should already be oriented correctly for printing.

I designed the two parts in Fusion 360, which I have never used prior to this project. If anyone wants access to the Fusion 360 files, please let me know. I don't know how to share them yet, but I understand that it is possible. I am happy to make the files available publicly.

title: Water level sensor bracket for self watering christmas tree!

description.text:
This is part of the automatic christmas tree watering device that I built with an Arduino Uno, a Relay module, 2 water level floating sensors and a submersible pump.

This is a bracket to mount 2 float sensors at slightly different heights. One of the floats will measure the low level of water, the other one measures the high level of water.

When the low level sensor is triggered, the arduino code will enable the pump until the high level sensor is triggered. Basically it keeps the water level at the base of the christmas tree between the high and low levels.

One comment that's important to note, the tube from the pump to the base of the christmas tree to have a small hole in it to allow for some air to get into the line. Otherwise, when you turn the pump on it will create a siphon and it will overfill the christmas tree. By adding the hole into the supply line tubing some air is allowed in when the pump is turned off and this breaks the vacuum that is causing the siphon.

Enjoy!

Bill of Materials:
1 submersible water pump
Tubing (to connect pumo in reservoir tank to bottom of christmas tree)
5 gallon bucket ( to act as the reservoir tank )
1 arduino uno
1 relay module
2 float sensors ( I used these ones : https://www.amazon.com/QX-Electronics-Switch-Plastic-Arduino/dp/B07252VQCM )

description.text:
This is a soap dish or sponge holder perfect for catching drips before they reach the counter. The design is based on the Zurich University of Applied Science (ZHAW) logo.

The holder consists of a top "dish" and a bottom "saucer". STL files are provided for a 6x10cm version that fits common hand soap, as well as a larger 9.5x12cm version that is more suited for sponges.

The design was created in OpenSCAD using the SymmetryCAD library. The dimensions can be easily modified in the code, and the logo could be swapped for another with a minor effort. The tesselation pattern can also be modified to any of the 17 wallpaper groups; the ZHAW logo is tiled with cmm symmetry.

I have always had problems with the wires coming out of my NES controllers and they would always become a mess. I decided to create this wire wrap to clip onto the controller so I could keep the wires nice and tidy.

NES-wrapper-2.stl and NES-wrapper-0.skp are actually the same iteration of design, I was just too lazy to rename the .SKP file. While printing, watch out - the thin clip part can easily delaminate from the platform and wreck the print. I would recommend a raft. The wire wrap should slide onto the controller as in the picture and the plug should snap into its respective clip. Depending on your settings, it may or may not fit your controller well. No worries - simply fudge with your Perimeter Width over Thickness setting until it fits. (Most will probably need to increase it. Mine is actually a lot higher than my Infill Width over Thickness.) Do not print in Polylactic Acid (PLA). It will be too hard a material and will either scratch your controller or be too hard to snap the plug onto.

title: This War of Mine Board Game Organiser Trays

description.text:
This War of Mine, the board game, is full of components, especially if you have its expansions and even more so if you wish to sleeve your cards. These trays were designed with ease of use, printing and with the ability to use the original box in mind.
I didn't go with the single piece insert, to make it easier to print, as well as to allow for use of individual trays while playing.

Printer:

Creality CR-10

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

10%

Notes:

NOTE: Remember to re-orient each component so that it lays flat on the print surface.

Brims are not 100% necessary, but I've found it much easier to make sure that the prints stick flat to the bed when I had an 8mm brim. And you need the prints to stick to the bed well, as these take a while to print, especially the token tray and card tray. This will also ensure the resulting print is the correct size and shape to fit in the box.

Infill is largely irrelevant as there aren't too many areas that will need it, but I wouldn't go below 10%.

Clean-up

Make sure you use some sandpaper along all the flat edges of each part, to make sure that everything will fit properly in the box.
Keep in mind that the additional tray might need a little more sanding in order to slide smoothly in its place.

Component Placement

Cards: I personally separate the cards in 4 piles for when I'm not saving a game.
1) Locations, Residents, Night Raids, Findings, Exploration, Crime Wave Residents & Night Raids
2) Visitors, Narrative Actions, Colors, Fate, Fittings, Ideas
3) Shelter, Characters, Objectives, Events, blank
4) All Expansion cards

While I'm putting things back in the box after saving a game, I separate the cards in 4 piles once again, by condensing the above to 3 piles, and putting the cards that are currently in use in the 4th pile, and the cards that have been 'removed from the game' in this same pile separated by the blank cards from the ones in use by the current game.

The tokens are placed as shown in the images, but feel free to use each compartment as you see fit. The only one I would recommend to keep as is (using them for the item tokens), are the four large compartments on the token tray.
As far as storing tokens that would be used for a saved game, I would recommend printing a second additional tray, and use it to store any tokens currently in use.

The miniature tray is separated in two compartments. The smaller one is for the expansion miniatures, and the larger one for regular character miniatures, as well as the heart of the city statue.

All booklets can go on top of the token tray. The board and any other larger flat components go on top of everything, and then the box can be closed with no overhang.

description.text:
This is the classic Spinout puzzle that was patented in 1972 by William Keister. It was manufactured by Binary Arts which later became Thinkfun, which has a page dedicated to it.

Note: My version does not have the quick reset functionality, because that makes it (too) easy to cheat.

There are 9 parts to print:

1x housing
1x carrier
1x dial1 (with flat bottom)
6x dial2-7 (with rounded bottoms)

The carrier has pegs which the dials will snap onto, and you need good layer adhesion to avoid damage when the dials are snapped in place. I used PLA, and had no problems, but you do need to apply quite a bit of force to snap them on. Trying to remove the dials will break the pegs, but there is no need to take them off again.

I used 0.2 mm layer height for everything except the housing, which I printed at 0.25 mm.

The housing will need supports in the slots along the sides, and this will be a pain to remove afterwards (took me 20 minutes with pliers, knife, and a flat headed screwdriver). In retrospect I could probably have placed the supports more carefully and avoided some of the work.

description.text:
This is a modified Original Prusa MK2 fan nozzle shroud.

The original fan nozzle did not fit well and also directed too much cooling toward the heated nozzle. This resulted in THERMAL RUNAWAY and lowering of the hot end temperature during printing.

I fixed my THERMA RUNAWAY ( and improved my PETG printing) problem by doing 3 things:

  1. Using the newest firmware version 3.1.0 (Nov 2017) there is a thermal calibration for the PID. I did a calibration for 240 degrees (for my PETG filament) and a calibration of 215 degrees (for my PLA filament) - this calibration will help stabilize the temperature during printing
  2. I changed the FILAMENT SETTINGS under the filament setting tab in Prusa Slic3r version 1.37.1 - for PETG the cooling is MAX 30% MIN 15% DISABLE FAN FOR FIRST 3 layers - for PLA cooling is MAX 80% MIN 75% DISABLE FAN FOR FIRST 3 layers
  3. Replaced the fan nozzle with the version included here
